success.question_text: The area of the design is about
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Measurement Data and Chance / Area

stimulus_1.text: Dylan drew this design on grid paper. Each square is 1 square centimetre.

review_1.column_1_text:
Solution

Count all the full squares (or almost full squares) and then match up the remaining parts of squares so that they together make a full square.

review_3.column_1_text:
So there are 10 full (or almost full) squares and together the remaining parts make about another six squares.

The area is about 16 square centimetres.

Tip

When counting an area on a grid, match up parts of squares to count as full squares.

success.question_text: Which of the following would also balance?
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Measurement Data and Chance / Mass

stimulus_1.text: The diagram shows a balance with discs and blocks.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

A set of scales is used to compare the masses of two objects. When one side of the scales is lower, the object on that side is heavier than the object on the other side.

success.question_text: In Sydney what time will it start?
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Measurement Data and Chance / Time

stimulus_2.text: The time in London is 10 hours behind Australian Eastern Standard Time. A concert begins in London at 5 pm on Saturday and is shown live on television in Sydney.

review_3.column_1_text:
London is 10 hours behind Sydney time, so Sydney time is 10 hours ahead of London time.

The concert will start in Sydney 10 hours after 5 pm Saturday.

Now 7 hours after 5 pm is midnight. Another 3 hours after that is 3 am.

In Sydney the concert will begin at 3 am Sunday.

Tip

In different places around the world, time can differ by up to 24 hours. Have a look at a map or globe that also shows time. Daylight saving time in the different countries will also affect time differences.

success.question_text: The length of the rectangle could be
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Measurement Data and Chance / Problem Solving

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

The opposite sides of a rectangle are equal in length. To find the perimeter, add all side lengths. Any missing lengths can be found by looking across the rectangle for matching lengths. To find the area, multiply the length by the breadth.

success.question_text: How long will it take until the tank is full?
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Measurement Data and Chance / Rates

stimulus_2.text:
A tank is empty but, when full, holds 720 litres.

A tap is turned on and water flows into the tank at the rate of 2 litres per second.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

Learn the conversions relating to time: 60 s = 1 min, 60 min = 1 h,
24 h = 1 day, 7 days = 1 week, 14 days = 2 weeks = 1 fortnight,
52 weeks = 1 year, 12 months = 1 year, 365 days = 1 year,
366 days = 1 leap year.

success.question_text: How many small boxes can she pack into the carton?
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Measurement Data and Chance / Capacity and Volume

stimulus_2.text: Reggie has small boxes that are 5 cm long, 4 cm wide and 3 cm high. She needs to pack them into a carton that is 40 cm long, 20 cm wide and 30 cm high.

review_5.column_1_text:
Tip

The volume of a rectangular prism is found by multiplying the length by breadth by height.

success.question_text: If the triangle has two sides that are equal in length, what could not be the length of one of the unknown sides?
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Measurement Data and Chance / Problem Solving

stimulus_1.text: One side of a triangle is 10 cm long. The perimeter of the triangle is 24 cm.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

An equilateral triangle has three sides equal and three angles equal; an isosceles triangle has two sides equal and two angles equal; a scalene triangle has sides of different lengths and angles of different sizes.

success.question_text: Which river is closest in length to the Darling?
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Measurement Data and Chance / Tables

stimulus_1.text: The table shows the lengths (in kilometres) of ten rivers.

review_3.column_1_text:
The length of the Darling is 2750 km.

The length of the Danube is 2800 km.

Difference in length between these two rivers is 50 km.

The Danube is the river that is closest in length to the Darling.

Tip

Sometimes it is necessary to consider all of the choices.

review_5.column_1_text:

success.question_text: If he finished the run at 10:24, what time did he start the run?
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Measurement Data and Chance / Time

stimulus_2.text: Daniel completed a fun run in 46 minutes.

review_3.column_1_text:
You need to find the time which is 46 minutes before 10:24.

First, 10:24 minus 24 minutes gives 10:00.

Now, from 10:00 minus another 22 minutes gives 9:38.

This means Daniel started the fun run at 9:38.

Tip

When subtracting time, it is easiest to subtract the hours and minutes separately. e.g. Subtract 2 h and 45 min from 9:30. Now 9:30 minus 2 h is 7:30. Now subtract 30 min to make 7:00 and then another 15 min. This means the answer is 6:45.

success.question_text: What is the depth of water in Container B?
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Measurement Data and Chance / Capacity and Volume

stimulus_1.text:
Two containers are in the shape of rectangular prisms.

Phillipa pours water into Container A.

She fills the container to the top. She then carefully pours all the water from
Container A into Container B.

review_4.column_1_text:
Tip

The volume of any prism can be found by multiplying the area of its base by its height.

success.question_text: If the car maintains this speed, at what time will it pass the next checkpoint 12 kilometres away?
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Measurement Data and Chance / Speed

stimulus_2.text: A rally car passes a checkpoint at 3:07 pm at a speed of 60 km/h.

review_3.column_1_text:
If a car travels at 60 km/h then it travels 1 km/min.

The rally car will travel the 12 kilometres to the next checkpoint in 12 minutes.

Adding 12 minutes to 3:07 will give 3:19.

The rally car will pass the next checkpoint at 3:19 pm.

Tip

success.question_text: If Juanita took 75 paces, what is the distance?
success.question_category_path: Numeracy / Measurement Data and Chance / Rates

stimulus_1.text:
Juanita takes 50 paces to walk 40 metres.

She counted her paces from the school canteen to the front gate.

review_3.column_1_text:
Tip

When a question asks you to work out a rate, you often need to use multiplication or division to find the answer.

The total length of board that Lily will need is about
